`await` suspends the surrounding async function and returns control to the event loop until the awaited promise settles. The function's local state (variables, the position in the source, the try/catch stack) is captured as a continuation, so when the promise resolves the runtime schedules a microtask that resumes the function with the resolved value (or throws the rejection at the await site). Nothing on the call stack is blocked; the rest of the program keeps running, and the awaiting function comes back later on its own microtask tick.

```js
async function fetchUser(id) {
  const res = await fetch(`/users/${id}`);
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);
  return res.json();
}
```
